(
  'Hidden Beaches of Calvia: 8 Secret Coves Worth Discovering',
  'hidden-beaches-calvia-secret-coves-worth-discovering',
  'Beyond the popular resorts, Calvia hides some of Mallorca''s most beautiful coves. Accessible by foot, boat, or dirt track, these beaches reward the adventurous.',
  '<p>Calvia''s coastline spans over 50 kilometers and includes more than 30 beaches, but the most magical ones are those you have to work a little to reach. These hidden coves, often sheltered by pine-covered cliffs and accessible only by footpath or boat, offer the kind of Mediterranean experience that crowded resort beaches cannot match.</p>

<h2>Cala Falco</h2>
<p>Tucked between Magaluf and Portals Vells, Cala Falco is a narrow cove reached by a ten-minute walk through pine forest. The water is exceptionally clear with a sandy bottom that glows turquoise in the midday sun. There are no facilities, which is precisely the point. Bring water, a snack, and a towel, and you have everything you need for a perfect Mediterranean morning.</p>

<h2>Portals Vells Caves Beach</h2>
<p>At the end of a dusty track south of Magaluf, three small beaches sit beneath limestone cliffs carved with ancient caves. The largest cave was likely used as a chapel by Genoese sailors in the medieval period. The swimming is superb, and snorkeling along the rocky edges reveals octopus, sea bream, and colorful wrasse.</p>

<h2>Calo des Moro (Calvia''s Version)</h2>
<p>Not to be confused with the famous Calo des Moro in Santanyi, Calvia has its own secluded rocky inlet near Cap de Cala Figuera. The access requires a scramble down a rocky path, but the reward is near-total solitude and water so clear you can count pebbles on the bottom from six meters above.</p>

<h2>Platja del Rei</h2>
<p>This small beach near Portals Nous is overlooked by most visitors heading to the nearby resort beaches. Protected by rocky outcrops, it offers calm waters ideal for swimming with small children. The adjacent restaurant provides drinks and simple food without the markup of the main tourist beaches.</p>

<h2>Cala Vinyes</h2>
<p>A residential beach that rarely appears in guidebooks, Cala Vinyes offers clean sand, shallow water, and a genuine local atmosphere. The small beach bar serves fresh-squeezed orange juice and basic bocadillos. On weekday mornings outside of peak summer, you may have the beach nearly to yourself.</p>

<h2>Practical Tips</h2>
<p>Visit hidden beaches early in the morning or after 4pm to avoid the warmest hours and the few visitors they do attract. Bring reef-safe sunscreen to protect the marine ecosystem. Carry out all rubbish, as these beaches have no cleanup services. Wear water shoes for rocky access points, and always check sea conditions before swimming at exposed coves.</p>',
