(
  'Hiking the Serra de Tramuntana: Best Trails Near Calvia',
  'hiking-serra-de-tramuntana-best-trails-near-calvia',
  'The UNESCO-listed Tramuntana mountains begin at Calvia''s doorstep. These five trails offer spectacular scenery for hikers of all levels.',
  '<p>The Serra de Tramuntana, a UNESCO World Heritage cultural landscape, forms the dramatic mountain backbone of northwestern Mallorca. Calvia sits at its southern gateway, making it an ideal base for exploring trails that range from gentle village walks to challenging mountain ascents.</p>

<h2>Trail 1: Calvia to Es Capdella (Easy)</h2>
<p>Distance: 8 km round trip. Duration: 3 hours. This gentle route through agricultural terraces and olive groves connects two of Calvia''s prettiest villages. The path is well-marked and mostly flat, passing ancient dry-stone walls, almond orchards, and traditional Mallorcan farmhouses. Es Capdella rewards you with excellent restaurants and a pretty village square for a post-hike refreshment.</p>

<h2>Trail 2: Galatzó Peak (Challenging)</h2>
<p>Distance: 14 km round trip. Duration: 5 to 6 hours. Galatzó is Calvia''s iconic mountain, its distinctive peak visible from much of the municipality. The trail from Es Capdella climbs through holm oak forest to exposed rocky terrain near the 1,026-meter summit. The 360-degree panorama from the top, encompassing the entire southwest coast and the central plain, is one of Mallorca''s finest. Start early and carry plenty of water.</p>

<h2>Trail 3: Cala Portals Vells Coastal Walk (Easy)</h2>
<p>Distance: 5 km round trip. Duration: 2 hours. A flat coastal path from Magaluf heading south along the peninsula to Portals Vells. Pine forest provides shade, and several viewpoints offer stunning perspectives over the sea. The trail ends at the three beaches of Portals Vells, perfect for a post-walk swim.</p>

<h2>Trail 4: La Reserva Puig de Galatzó (Moderate)</h2>
<p>Distance: 4 km circuit. Duration: 2 to 3 hours. This privately managed nature reserve near Puigpunyent features a well-maintained trail through forested gorges, past waterfalls, and over wooden bridges. It is particularly beautiful after autumn rains when the waterfalls are at their most impressive. There is an admission fee, but the infrastructure makes this an excellent option for families.</p>

<h2>Trail 5: GR221 Section - Es Capdella to Estellencs (Challenging)</h2>
<p>Distance: 16 km one way. Duration: 6 to 7 hours. This section of Mallorca''s famous long-distance trail, the Dry Stone Route, passes through some of the most dramatic mountain scenery on the island. Ancient stone paths, mountain passes, and sweeping views of both the coast and interior make this a memorable full-day expedition. Arrange transport at the far end or make it a two-day trek with an overnight in Estellencs.</p>

<h2>Essential Hiking Tips</h2>
<p>The best hiking months are October through May. Summer heat makes mountain hiking dangerous. Always carry more water than you think you need, at least 2 liters per person. Tell someone your planned route and expected return time. Wear proper hiking boots on all but the easiest trails. Download offline maps, as mobile signal is unreliable in the mountains.</p>',
