(
  'Mallorca''s Wildlife: Birdwatching and Marine Life Around Calvia',
  'mallorca-wildlife-birdwatching-marine-life-calvia',
  'From Eleonora''s falcons nesting on sea cliffs to Posidonia meadows teeming with life, Calvia''s natural habitats are richer than most visitors realize.',
  '<p>Calvia sits at the intersection of mountain, coastal, and marine ecosystems, creating an extraordinarily rich environment for wildlife. Whether you are a dedicated naturalist or simply curious about the nature around you, the municipality offers rewarding encounters with both common and rare species.</p>

<h2>Birdwatching Highlights</h2>
<p>The rocky coastline between Portals Vells and Cap de Cala Figuera hosts a breeding colony of Eleonora''s falcon, one of the most spectacular raptors in the Mediterranean. These elegant birds arrive in April from Madagascar and can be observed hunting insects on the wing from the clifftop paths. Early morning and late afternoon offer the best sighting opportunities.</p>
<p>The Galatzó mountain area supports booted eagles, red kites, and peregrine falcons. The diverse forest habitats also harbor Balearic warblers, Marmora''s warblers, and firecrest, all easier to hear than to see in the dense undergrowth. The patient observer will be rewarded with sightings of hoopoe, golden oriole, and bee-eater during migration seasons.</p>

<h2>Marine Life</h2>
<p>The waters around the Malgrats Islands, protected as a marine reserve since 1999, have recovered dramatically. Snorkelers and divers regularly encounter grouper, moray eels, barracuda, and octopus. The Posidonia oceanica seagrass meadows that carpet much of the shallow seabed are vital nurseries for fish and produce significant amounts of oxygen.</p>
<p>Bottlenose dolphins are regularly spotted from the coast, particularly in the early morning. Loggerhead sea turtles occasionally appear in Calvia waters during summer, and the municipality participates in regional conservation efforts to protect nesting sites.</p>

<h2>Land Wildlife</h2>
<p>The pine martens of the Tramuntana foothills are rarely seen but leave obvious signs: scat on trails, scratch marks on trees, and raided fig trees in autumn. Wild goats, descended from domestic herds, inhabit the higher reaches of Galatzó. The Mallorcan midwife toad, an endemic species once thought extinct, has been successfully reintroduced to suitable habitats in the municipality.</p>

<h2>Conservation Efforts</h2>
<p>Calvia has been at the forefront of environmental conservation in the Balearics. The municipality''s Blue Flag beaches, marine protected areas, and investment in sustainable tourism demonstrate a commitment to preserving the natural heritage that makes this area so special. Visitors can contribute by respecting protected areas, avoiding anchoring on Posidonia meadows, and supporting local conservation organizations.</p>',
  'https://images.pexels.com/photos/1624496/pexels-photo-1624496.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=1260&h=750&dpr=2',
