  'Calvia in Winter: Why the Off-Season Is the Best Time to Visit',
  'calvia-winter-off-season-best-time-visit',
  'While summer gets the crowds, winter reveals Calvia''s true character: almond blossoms, uncrowded trails, cozy restaurants, and a pace of life that lets you truly experience Mallorca.',
  '<p>Most visitors to Calvia come between June and September, when temperatures are high and beaches are busy. But those who discover the municipality between November and March find something arguably more beautiful: a quieter, more authentic Mallorca that rewards slower exploration.</p>

<h2>The Climate Advantage</h2>
<p>Calvia''s winter climate is remarkably mild. Daytime temperatures typically range from 12 to 18 degrees Celsius, with over 300 days of sunshine per year. Rain falls occasionally, usually in short bursts that leave the landscape refreshed and fragrant. Compared to northern European winters, it feels almost tropical.</p>

<h2>Almond Blossom Season</h2>
<p>Late January through February transforms the Calvia countryside into a sea of white and pink blossoms. The almond groves between Calvia village and Es Capdella are particularly spectacular, with ancient trees creating clouds of petals against a backdrop of green mountains. This natural spectacle attracts photographers from across Europe and is genuinely one of the most beautiful sights in the Mediterranean.</p>

<h2>Hiking Paradise</h2>
<p>The Tramuntana trails that are dangerously hot in summer become perfect in winter. Crisp mornings, clear mountain air, and often snow-dusted peaks create ideal hiking conditions. The trails are virtually empty, and the quality of light for photography is exceptional during the shorter, lower-angled winter days.</p>

<h2>Culinary Comfort</h2>
<p>Winter is when Calvia''s restaurants are at their most authentic. The tourist-oriented menus give way to seasonal Mallorcan cooking: hearty sopas mallorquinas, slow-cooked arroz brut, roasted lamb with mountain herbs, and fresh-pressed olive oil from the recent harvest. Restaurant owners have more time to talk, and the atmosphere is noticeably warmer and more personal.</p>

<h2>Lower Prices, Higher Quality</h2>
<p>Accommodation prices drop 40 to 60 percent outside of peak season. Flights are cheaper. Restaurants and attractions are less crowded. Paradoxically, the quality of experience often improves precisely because the reduced visitor numbers allow businesses to provide more attentive service.</p>

<h2>What to Know</h2>
<p>Some coastal businesses close entirely from November through February. Check opening times in advance. A rental car is more important in winter, as public transport frequency decreases. Pack layers: mornings and evenings are cool, but midday sun can still be surprisingly warm. And bring a camera: winter light in Calvia is photographer''s gold.</p>',
  'https://images.pexels.com/photos/1179229/pexels-photo-1179229.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=1260&h=750&dpr=2',
  '817dcd87-2363-4946-8c62-a7dde42e9611',
  'Anna Lindberg',
  '2025-12-29T08:00:00Z',
  7,
  'Calvia in Winter: Why Off-Season Is Best | Calvia Blog',
  'Discover why winter is the best time to visit Calvia, Mallorca. Almond blossoms, uncrowded trails, cozy restaurants, and lower prices await.',
  false
